\begin_layout Section
Minimality and Column Reducedness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For many polynomial matrix computation problems, we would like the output
 matrix to be not only easy to describe, but also convenient to use.
 This usually means the column degrees or the more general shifted column
 degrees are small comparing to other matrices that are right unimodularly
 equivalent.
 For example a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}=\left[x,x^{2},x^{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 with column degrees 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,2,2\right]$
\end_inset

 can be unimodularly reduced to a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}=\left[x,x,x^{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 with column degrees 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,1,2\right]$
\end_inset

, which is more desirable with lower degrees.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To unimodularly reduce a matrix to one with lower column degrees, we can
 look at its
\emph on
 leading column coefficient matrix
\emph default
, which is defined as follows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Given a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\in\mathbb{K}\left[x\right]^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

, the leading column coefficient matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A & =\lcoeff\left(\mathbf{A}\right)\\
 & =\left[\lcoeff\left(\mathbf{a}_{1}\right),\dots,\lcoeff\left(\mathbf{a}_{k}\right)\right]\\
 & =\left[\coeff\left(\mathbf{a}_{1},\deg\left(\mathbf{a}_{1}\right)\right),\dots,\coeff\left(\mathbf{a}_{k},\deg\left(\mathbf{a}_{k}\right)\right)\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 can be unimodularly reduced to another matrix with lower column degrees
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lcoeff\left(\mathbf{A}\right)$
\end_inset

 is not full-rank.
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the following, we assume with out loss of generality that matrices have
 columns arranged in increasing column degrees.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:columnOperationToReduceDegree"

\end_inset

Given a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\in\mathbb{K}\left[x\right]^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

 with no zero columns.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\lcoeff\left(\mathbf{A}\right)$
\end_inset

 is not full-rank, then there is a unimodular matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdeg\left(\mathbf{A}\mathbf{U}\right)\prec\cdeg\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We may assume the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 are arranged in increasing column degrees.
 Let the column degrees of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[d_{1},\dots,d_{n}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\lcoeff\left(\mathbf{A}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th column 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of the first 
\begin_inset Formula $i-1$
\end_inset

 columns.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}=A'a$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 is the submatrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 consists of the first 
\begin_inset Formula $i-1$
\end_inset

 columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\left[a_{1},\dots,a_{i-1}\right]^{T}\in\mathbb{K}^{(i-1)\times1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{U}=\begin{bmatrix}1 &  &  &  & -a_{1}x^{d_{i}-d_{1}}\\
 & 1 &  &  & -a_{2}x^{d_{i}-d_{2}}\\
 &  & \ddots &  & \vdots\\
 &  &  & 1 & -a_{i-1}x^{d_{i}-d_{i-1}}\\
 &  &  &  & 1\\
 &  &  &  &  & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  &  & 1
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}=\mathbf{A}\mathbf{U}$
\end_inset

 has column degrees 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[d_{1},\dots,d_{i-1},\bar{d}{}_{i},d_{i+1},\dots,d_{n}\right],$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{d}_{i}<d_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The leading column coefficient matrix can also help to determine the degree
 of the matrix.
