\begin_layout Section
Nullspace Basis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nullspace bases are closely related to order bases, as can be seen from
 the following definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}\in\mathbb{K}\left[x\right]^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

, a polynomial matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}\in\mathbb{K}\left[x\right]^{n\times k}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}$
\end_inset

-minimal (right) nullspace basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

 if the following properties hold: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

 is full-rank and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}$
\end_inset

-column reduced (or equivalently, the leading column coefficient matrix
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\vec{s}}\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

 is full-rank).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}\cdot\mathbf{N}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}\in\mathbb{K}\left[x\right]^{n}$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}\mathbf{q}=0$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a linear combination of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

, that is, there exists some polynomial vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}=\mathbf{N}\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Note that in the problem of nullspace basis computation, the column dimension
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

 is usually unknown in advance.
 Knowing the column dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

 also gives us the rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $n-k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that the module 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left(\mathbf{F},\vec{\sigma}\right)\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 does not depend on the shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Minimal nullspace bases can be directly computed via order basis computation.
 Indeed if the order 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{F},\sigma,\vec{s}\right)$
\end_inset

-basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset

 is high enough, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset

 contains a 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}$
\end_inset

-minimal nullspace basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

.
 However, this approach may require the order 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to be quite high.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}$
\end_inset

 is uniform, then its minimal nullspace bases can have degree up to 
\begin_inset Formula $md$
\end_inset

.
 In that case the order 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 would need to be set to 
\begin_inset Formula $d+md$
\end_inset

 in the order basis computation in order to fully compute a minimal nullspace
 basis.
 The fastest method of computing such a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{F},d+md\right)$
\end_inset

-basis would cost 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{\sim}\left(n^{\omega}\left\lceil m^{2}d/n\right\rceil \right)$
\end_inset

 using the algorithm from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "za2009"

\end_inset

.
 We can see from this cost that there is room for improvement when 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is large.
 For example, in the worst case when 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\Theta\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

, this cost would be 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{\sim}\left(n^{\omega+1}d\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This points to a root cause for the inefficiency in this approach.
 Namely, when 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is large, the computed nullspace basis, which can have a column dimension
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $n-m$
\end_inset

, is a much smaller subset of the order basis computed.
 Hence considerable effort is put in the computation of order basis elements
 that are not part of a nullspace basis.
 A key to reducing the cost is therefore to reduce such computation of unneeded
 order basis elements, which is achieved in our algorithm by only using
 order basis computation to compute partial nullspace bases of low degrees.
\end_layout

\end_inset


